Errors are only triggered when something goes seriously wrong - a syntax error in the SQL and things like that. When the user is not found the query itself was successful, so the success callback is triggered. But since nothing matched your query, null is returned. And the reason your code breaks is that you are trying to access a property on something that is null. You success handler should be something like this:

``` js
if (user) {
    console.log(user);
    console.log(user.token_sent);
    res.send('found it!');
} else {
    res.send("nothing found");
}
```

At the moment sequelize does not support transient properties. By default `toJSON` just returns the attributes of the model, which are saved in `.values`

You can however just overwrite the toJSON method on instances of a DAO, like this:

``` javascript
var User = sequelize.define('user', {
  id: Sequelize.INTEGER,
  name: Sequelize.STRING
}, {
  instanceMethods: {
    toJSON: function () {
      var json = this.values;

      json.type= 'user';
      return json;
    }
  }
});
```

